From 479b2243f3b13ec7195cd71f8018cb5d8d342ddf Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: dfattal <dfattal@gmail.com>
Date: Sun, 19 Jul 2026 18:34:44 +0900
Subject: inline-3d(#22): suppress canvas + overlay quads the weave draw-back
 owns
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Under Option B the woven output is drawn back WHOLE-WINDOW with kSrcOver,
which composites honestly against alpha. Two consequences the per-tile kSrc
draw-back used to paper over:

  - the inline-3D CANVAS resource (the raw side-by-side content) is weave
    INPUT only, but the page still painted it, so it showed through wherever
    the woven tile was transparent (visible under rounded tile corners as a
    tighter-radius SBS copy underneath);
  - the isolated 2D OVERLAY resources are composited over the weave by the
    display processor, so a page-painted copy is a second source and doubles
    against the DP's wherever the two don't align.

Both are the same fix: let the weave draw-back be the single source and stop
painting those quads. DirectRenderer grows a per-frame ResourceIdSet checked
at the top of ShouldSkipQuad — it hooks the existing per-quad `continue` in
DrawRenderPass, so it covers the plain and BSP-sorted paths alike. Display
fills the set from the aggregated frame's canvas + overlay resources.

Gated on the frame actually having inline-3D rects: with no weave in flight
nothing would draw them back, and suppressing would blank the canvas rather
than fix anything. Note the failure mode is asymmetric — if a frame ever has
inline-3D rects but the weave does not land, this blanks rather than glitches.

Hardware-validated on Leia (gallery + wall-3d): SBS no longer shows through
transparent woven pixels, and rounded tile corners composite correctly
instead of being stamped over.

